t4763.text: But I think it's important that we don't feel afraid to speak about our grief, to work through the pain together, and, if the time feels right and the energy is there, to allow ourselves space to talk about positive change.

t4764.text: I feel thats one thing I, and many others like me, are experiencing right now. Apathy. A sense of being overwhelmed. And it's hard to acknowledge, accept and speak to. It's hard to discuss and talk about- it's not a fun topic. And I know we can't always engage. That's ok too.

t4765.text: I know. It's all pretty hopeless. And sometimes it's pretty overwhelming. I guess that's why I avoided it, and will, at times, continue to - and that's fine sometimes. But Id like to try, when I have the energy, to find ways to cope more positively. And to talk about it.

t4766.text: I'm also trying to think about how I can do something with the sense of Apathy. Ways to reduce my own personal footprint, as well as ways to engage socially, financially and with my community. I'm open to hearing about groups trying to actively move us toward a positive change.

t4767.text: I'm only just starting out on a journey that many people are well into. And whilst I don't have any answers, I'm at least acknowledging this pain. I'm so very sorry that it took me so long. If you're hurting too, the above article helped cement the idea that I'm far from alone.

t4768.text: I dealt with it for a long while like many of us did. Head planted firmly in the sand. Even as those close to me spoke of their grief- I listened, and believed them. But I had to at times avoid, or change the subject- as I wasn't able to engage at the time. I'm ashamed of that.

t4769.text: It's a grief. Just like losing someone. It comes with almost every emotion available- fear, sadness, loss, anger, shame. It hits when you least expect, it's unpredictable & hurts like hell. Some of us have felt this for decades. Many of us have only been experiencing it recently.

t4770.text: Many of those close to me have been speaking of it for years. There's an upset, even a deep depression you feel when you start to piece together all the scientific facts and face the terrible realities. They call it "Climate Grief". I can't think of a better way to put it.

t4771.text: It's been a hard month here in Aus. The fires are unthinkable, and the next thought- climate change- It's horrific. We're all feeling a lot of pain, either directly or via friends & family hurt, and it's taking it's toll on me, and many of my loved ones.https://www.yesmagazine.org/health-happiness/2018/08/09/the-best-medicine-for-my-climate-grief/ …

t7195.text: Lastly, remember you have power. You have purchasing power, voting power, power to communicate and influence. You have the power to use your skills for good. You have grassroots power and community power. Don't waste it.

t7196.text: Get other people on board. Talk about this at work. With your family. At school or university. Show people how easy it can be.

t7197.text: Importantly, please vote for a party that takes the climate crisis seriously.

t7198.text: Don't try to be perfect. Just try.

t7199.text: Plant natives in your garden to attract bees and birds. Reconsider your lawn if you can.

t7200.text: Go secondhand where you can. Cheaper, cooler too.

t7202.text: For the love of God stop buying disposable plastic bottles and coffee cups. So unnecessary.

t7203.text: Volunteer with or donate to local tree planting and reforestation groups.

t7204.text: Compost or worm farm your food scraps. Methane generated by rotting organic matter in landfill has a non trivial impact.

t7205.text: The true power of sport has been on show over the past 24 hrs; Athletes donating generously, sports announcing fundraising events. Sport is a unifier, it brings people together. While results are superfluous at a time like this- sports power as a vehicle for genorousity is not.

t7206.text: Switch to green energy at home (and at work if possible).

t7207.text: Reconsider air travel, especially for work. Push for teleconferencing.

t7208.text: Think about reducing carbon miles on what you consume by shopping local as much as possible. Food and non consumables alike.

t7209.text: Recycle your soft plastics at any Woolies or Coles. And try to buy less of it. Preference products made with paper, glass or aluminium packaging.

t7210.text: Move your money to banks and super that have divested from fossil fuels. It's not that hard. Business owners especially, please.

t7211.text: Eat less meat. Try at least being vegetarian for the weekdays. Or for one meal a day. Don't have to be vegan, but cut down, especially on beef.

t7212.text: Don't drive to work. Ride a bike, walk, get public transport.

t7213.text: Give up some nice things in your life. Sacrifice comfort either now or a lot more in the future.

t7214.text: Donate to fire fighters and wildlife rehabilitation.

t7215.text: Things you might be able to do: (1/19)
